There are two aspects to this question: 1) coronavirus-related layoff risk and 2) labour force participation rate - even if hiring stays strong, then unemployment can rise if the number of more discouraged/disabled workers who come back into the labour force looking for work is higher than the number of jobs being added. NB that when you include these workers (the discouraged, part-timers looking for more), the real unemployment figure is more like 7% and probably higher if you include some number of disabled people who could find work in a sufficiently tight labour market.

We are nearly two months into this 10 month question. To simulate a random walk I put on a surgical mask, closed my eyes and walked thru my house while listening to the stock market. I used the red/green of the 3 major market indexes to tell me when to stop and when to go. I turned at each stop a quarter turn to the left. I then counted the number of times I bumped into a wall and divided that by the number of times I stopped. My result is the same as this is an election year and employment is still a lagging indicator. Even with a potential 20% market correction we are unlikely to see unemployment increase significantly in 8 months.

The unemployment rate jumped to 3.6 percent because more people are entering the labor force. Thus, the number of people counted in the labor force is growing. Yet, the rate of GDP growth is slowing. The time series itself is not complicated. Different models (ETS, ARIMA) give almost the same probability that the 4% limit will be broken (14%). However, history tells us that the unemployment curve is severely disrupted when there is a recession. From former recessions we learn that on average the unemployment rate rises with 0.23% per month. At the moment (data Nov 2019) we are at 3.5%. It would take little more than 2 months before the limit of 4% is broken. So the real question is: will there be a recession in the first nine months of 2020? The Federal Reserve Bank of New York has a model. The success rate of this model in the period from 1961 up to now is 5/9=56%: in the nine situations where the model had a peak probability for a recession of 40% or less (about what is predicted for Aug 2020), the recession did materialise in 5 cases. However: the Fed did react swiftly when the spread (this is the predictor that the Fed's model uses) went negative in the period from Jun 2019 to Sep 2019. So this might have an impact. Therefore I take my forecast a bit lower than 56% and put it on 40%.

Unemployment will start to go up by the summer of 2020. Recessions tend to start between 6-24 months after the rate of the 3 month treasury bonds rises above the 10 year treasury bond. Also recessions are about 6-12 months away after that inversion reinverts so that the 3 month is back to normal, being below the 10 year rate. The rate inverted in May 2019, they deinverted in October 2019 about a month after the new york fed had started pumping about $160 billion per day into the repo market. The fed rate is only 1 indicator for recession, the quantitative easing by the fed is another indicator.

This a 'do you think economic growth will weaken' question in disguise, where one has to remember that the unemployment rate is a lagging indicator of economic activity. The previous inversion of the yield curve suggests that a recession will happen. The fact that yield curve inversion has stopped is largely unimportant. See this weeks article on this very topic in the Economist. URL: https://www.economist.com/united-states/2019/11/14/americas-yield-curve-is-no-longer-inverted

The last time the U3 reached 4% was January 2019, and in the past 24 months it has reached or exceeded 4% seven times (including Jan 2019) [1] - which is ~29% of the time. However, last month it was just 3.6% and there are signs that the U.S. economy is holding up well despite a global slowdown [2] - so, unless economic conditions change, as of now I find it unlikely that the 4% mark will be reached despite a base rate that indicates this is likely. I mostly hold this view because the unemployment data shows that, barring a recession, the U3 rarely rises steeply - and a recession seems unlikely at the moment. I will revise if the unemployment rate ticks up from 3.6% in the next few months.
